      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why K-Words Are Powerful in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>K is worth 5 points — the same as J and the third-highest single-tile value after Q and Z. With only one K tile in the bag, drawing it is relatively rare, which makes knowing how to use it effectively all the more important. The best K-words leverage K's natural point value alongside other premium consonants like Z, X, and double-K combinations.</p>
      <p>Words like KOLHOZY and KIBBUTZ rank among the highest-scoring words in the entire game regardless of starting letter. Even shorter K-words like KLUTZ (18 points) and KVETCH (18 points) deliver exceptional value for their length. K also combines naturally with common vowels, giving you flexible placement options on tight boards.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing K-Words</h2>
      <p>K demands a strategic approach. Here's how to squeeze maximum value from your K tile:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Target premium squares:</strong> K on a double-letter square is worth 10 points before you even count the rest of the word. On a triple-letter, that's 15 points from one tile. Always scan for premium placement.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Learn the two-letter K-words:</strong> KA and KI are both valid and score 6 points each. These are essential for parallel plays and tight-board situations.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Combine K with Z or Y:</strong> Words like KLUTZ, KLUTZY, and KAZOO pair K with other high-value tiles for devastating scores. Hold K if you see Z or Y coming.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hold K too long:</strong> Unlike blank tiles, K doesn't help with bingos (7-letter plays). If you can't score 15+ points with K in one turn, play it for whatever you can get rather than clogging your rack.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use KN- words:</strong> English has many KN- words (KNACK, KNEEL, KNIFE, KNOCK). These are familiar and easy to spot when you have K+N on your rack.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Key K-Word Patterns to Memorise</h2>
      <p>Recognising letter patterns helps you spot K-words faster during gameplay. The most productive K-word patterns include:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>KN- words:</strong> KNACK, KNAVE, KNEAD, KNEEL, KNIFE, KNIGHT, KNIT, KNOCK, KNOT, KNOW — the silent K gives you surprising plays</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>-CK endings:</strong> Many words end in CK. Play them backwards from K: KICK, KNACK, KNOCK — you're building towards your K tile</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>KI- words:</strong> KIBBUTZ, KIBITZ, KICK, KILO, KIMONO, KINDLE, KINKY, KIOSK — the KI combination is extremely productive</span></li>
      </ul>

